title: For Sale:  Brown Bess-2nd Pattern
postcontent:
Up for sell is a beautiful, older reproduction of the Pedersoli 2nd Model Brown Bess with Bayonet, Scabbard, and Belt. This Second Model Brown Bess is an exact reproduction of the musket manufactured in England by Grice in 1762. Features a European walnut one-piece fullstock 54" long, satin finish, with 2 1/2" drop and 14 1/2" trigger pull. Barrel is .75 caliber left in the bright, 42" long tapered round 1.250" at breech to .890" at muzzle, smoothbore (.750" diameter). Front sight is steel stud which serves as bayonet lug. Flintlock uses 1" flints. Brass furniture, lockplate border line engraved "Grice 1762" on tail w/ crown and "GR" ahead of hammer. Single trigger. Sling swivels, steel head ramrod (10x32 male thread). Gun is 58 1/4" in overall length and weighs 9 lbs. 

Overall in excellent condition. There is a small chip of wood missing on the forearm edge at barrel, but not a major blemish at all. More pictures available upon request.

Shipping will be separate and depends on location. Will not ship overseas. Will arrange a meeting if you live in close proximity. $850 or best offer. Cash only.

title: For Sale:  2000 F-250 Super Duty (7.3L turbodiesel) 4x4 OR TRADE
postcontent:
For sale / partial trade is my 2000 F-250 Extended Cab 4x4 7.3L turbodiesel.

Asking $4500 plus a HONDA (prefer civic hatchback, 2 door better, 4 door ok) in running or non-running condition depending on year / condition for me to keep and use.

OR 

Asking $5700 reasonably firm.

OR

A spectacular trade involving no cash. Gotta be seriously damn spectacular though.

See Below For Details

Automatic 5spd w/ overdrive. Makings of a great work/play truck. A little rough around the edges, solid where it counts. Would make great plow truck.

The Good:

Super Duty - Hitch receiver and tow harness adapter
A/C and Cruise Control
4x4 (manual hubs, shifter on the floor)
Power windows, locks
Linex liner
Toolbox
Good tailgate
Front clip in good shape


Long list of new and newer parts on truck:

Transmission rebuilt
Turbo rebuild
Turbo pedestal and plunger replaced
Two injectors replaced
Two 5 month old Interstate batteries
New starter
New water pump
New glow plug relay
New intake heater relay
New both sides in front
Upper, lower arms
Upper, lower ball joints
Steering stabalizer
Wheel bearings
4 shocks
New drive belts
New air filter
New high pressure oil pump
Drivers headlight assembly replaced
Nice bulbs recently installed
Recently had oil change and tune
Used lucas oil products in everything
New L/R hub, bearings, internal parking brake, rotor, pads
New fuel filter

Have receipts for many of above parts and some service records - oldest is an oil change receipt dated during the year 2000

The Bad: Truck's block heater needs to be plugged in overnight to ensure reliable starts in cold weather.

The Ugly:
Truck has a cracked windshield (not shattered)
driver's seat isn't so hot (truck now comes with brand-new RealTree seat cover)
driver's side rear door has some damage (dented and then pulled out)
Bed has a little wheel well rust and some dings and dents (no huge wounds)
Cupholder/ashtray in dash broken put present
Different keys for ignition and door (driver's outer door lock doesn't work with key)
A few bumper dings/dents. I'd give the body overall a strong 7/10


Truck has 392k miles, mostly highway. First owner was construction company, used for management transportation between job sites, then put into general service with a friend of mine before it came to me. Yep, that's a few, but it's a strong runner (stupidly reliable 7.3L International engine - they used to put 'em in semi trucks) and is good for a "running with room for cosmetic improvement" work/play truck.

Was originally interested in truck to use for my small business, would keep but don't have a requirement for a big truck currently (business concept hasn't worked out ... yet). Transmission was rebuilt less than 10k miles ago. Expected to put another $1k - $2k into it (tires and eventually injectors) and put another 200k miles on it.

KBB value for 'fair' condition, including odometer miles, somewhere north of $8500.

Clean Colorado Title. Can provide VIN for carfax to prove no accidents (on your dime).

OFFER MUST INCLUDE SPECIFIED PRICE IN CASH.

title: For Sale:  9mm "Largo" $20 each or $70 for all 4
postcontent:
The 9mm Largo is the Spanish version, or designation, for the Belgium 9mm Bayard Long, also called the 9mm Bergmann-Bayard Long. The Spanish military adopted the 9mm Bermann in 1908 and renamed  or designated the cartridge as the "9mm Largo".
The cartridge dimensions are 9x23mm, but this is not the same cartridge as the 9x23mm Winchester. 
Do NOT use a 9x23mm Winchester in a 9mm Largo Pistol!  It is to high pressure!
The 9x23mm Winchester produces much higher pressure than the 9mm Largo; however, both have the same 
outside case dimensions.  There are many pistols chambered in the 9mm Largo:
Bergmann-Bayard M1910, Star Modelo Militar 1920, Astra Modelo 400 (1921) 
Star Modelo Militar 1921, Star Modelo 1922, Star Modelo A,  Jo-Lo-Ar Pistol

title: For Sale:  9mm "Largo" $20 each or $70 for all 4
postcontent:
The 9mm Largo is the Spanish version, or designation, for the Belgium 9mm Bayard Long, also called the 9mm Bergmann-Bayard Long. The Spanish military adopted the 9mm Bermann in 1908 and renamed  or designated the cartridge as the "9mm Largo".
The cartridge dimensions are 9x23mm, but this is not the same cartridge as the 9x23mm Winchester. 
Do NOT use a 9x23mm Winchester in a 9mm Largo Pistol!  It is to high pressure!
The 9x23mm Winchester produces much higher pressure than the 9mm Largo; however, both have the same 
outside case dimensions.  There are many pistols chambered in the 9mm Largo:
Bergmann-Bayard M1910, Star Modelo Militar 1920, Astra Modelo 400 (1921) 
Star Modelo Militar 1921, Star Modelo 1922, Star Modelo A,  Jo-Lo-Ar Pistol
Star Modelo AS,  and a few carbines :  Destroyer, Onena, and Ignacio Zubillaga Carbines.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger Single Six old-model (1959)
postcontent:
As the pictures show, this gun has some cosmetic issues, but its mechanical condition is excellent.  The original finish has been worn away in places over the last fifty-four years, and there're a few small scratches under the tip of the barrel from when it was poking out of my holster and I sat on concrete.  It remains the most accurate handgun I've ever fired, able to hit golf balls at forty feet when I'm paying attention to what I'm doing.

For those unfamiliar with the Single Six, it's a single-action .22LR six-shot revolver (they didn't start offering .22WMR cylinders 'til two years after this one was made) with four hammer positions (ready to fire, load/unload, just been fired, and a 'safety notch' just far enough back to keep the hammer away from the firing pin so it won't go off if dropped/bumped).  A spring-loaded rod under the barrel is used to eject spent casings, and disassembly for cleaning involves an easy, push-button rod release.

Two holsters included, one leather hip-holster nearly as old as the pistol is, but in decent condition, and a nylon holster with straps for a shoulder rig that can be unclipped to wear it on the hip.  Included ammo is six rounds of cast-fragmentation self-defense loads, twelve rounds of Stinger that have noticeably more kick than most .22's, and roughly two hundred rounds of assorted cheap ammo, mostly Federal.

title: For Sale:  CHIAPPA RHINO 357 2'
postcontent: Defense revolver, offers great concealability thanks to a very unusual profile. The flat cylinder grants maximum comfort. The new Chiappa Rhino barrel is aligned with the bottom most chamber which is the key component to Rhino's tame characteristics. The position of the barrel lowers the center of gravity and yields a centerline of the bore more in line with the shooter's arm allowing for the most natural "point ability" while engaging a target. This characteristic also drastically reduces both recoil and muzzle flip which insures subsequent shots to be on target faster than ever before. The reduction of the recoil allows for the use of ultra light alloys to be used in the construction of the Rhino minimizing any adverse effect. The flat sided cylinder design of the Rhino reduces the typical revolver profile allowing greater concealment. Featuring both double and single action characteristics, the single action is actuated by a hammer cocking device that engages the unexposed hammer to prepare to fire. The versions of 2" Rhino with Double Action only (item codes ending with "D" instead of "DS") do not have an external hammer. All 2" barrel Rhino revolvers are supplied with a beautiful leather holster included.

Initially designed with the precision shooter in mind, the folks at LaRue Tactical queried trusted individuals in the precision shooting community what they would prefer in a grip. #1 Survival Bug Out Camp Necessity IN WINTER!  Everyone has weapons, but everyone seems to forget what will you do to keep you warm in the Winter? NOTE-Gas has several major issues.  1-No power=no working gas pumps; 2-Gas DOES NOT last forever, and only has a shelf life of about 7 months from the time it's made (not forever)!  So long term Bug Outs who expect to use gas generators, they are not the answer, nor the smartest long-term idea!  But I bypassed all of these issues...

Remember, no one can do it all alone.  Pool resources.  You need to find like minded people who will watch your back, and you can trust in any disaster.
